<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06028131 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06028131 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  US; GOVERNMENT; TRADE; OFFICE; CHANGE; IMAGE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The Federal Trade Commission, slowly shifting from the laissez-faire attitudeof the Reagan administration, is starting to use its antitrust muscles andrenew its interest in cases that affect the public's pocketbook.;    Theagency has begun to challenge manufacturers trying to limit price discountingby retailers and is investigating possible price fixing in the infant-formulaindustry.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  FTC TAKES ACTIVIST STANCECRITICS: U.S. AGENCY QUIET UNDER REAGAN  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The number of cases involving false and deceptive advertising, another arearegulated by the agency, is also up.;    &quot;There is a new vigor and commitmentat the agency,&quot; said Michael Pertschuk, a commission member from 1974 to 1984who is co-director of the Advocacy Institute, a public interest group inWashington.;    &quot;This infant-formula investigation might have been broughtunder the Reagan administration, but the economists at the FTC then would havefigured out why price fixing is good for consumers,&quot; he said.;    In theformula case, the agency subpoenaed the records of all leading makers ofinfant formula after state welfare officials and consumer groups complainedthat the manufacturers had raised prices in a uniform way over the pastdecade.;    Other efforts;  Although the infant-formula case has attracted themost attention, the agency has undertaken other efforts, including these:;   (check) It recently settled the first retail price-fixing case in eight years,and an inquiry is expected to result soon in a call for action against theU.S. subsidiary of Nintendo, the Japanese producer of video games, over itssales policies.;    (check) In the first deceptive-advertising case since 1985to be brought against an advertising agency, the FTC challenged television adsfor a toy manufacturer that said -- erroneously -- that a doll could twirlaround on its own.;    (check) The agency has filed a growing number ofconsumer-protection lawsuits, including the first involving a &quot;900&quot; phonenumber.;    Just how aggressive the agency will become under the Bushadministration is uncertain, but Janet D. Steiger, appointed FTC chairwoman inAugust 1989, is getting much of the credit for the agency's new mood.;   Coordinating efforts;  Steiger also is moving to coordinate federal and stateconsumer-protection actions, something that did not happen often during theReagan years.;    Some public-interest advocates, however, are not impressed.;   &quot;The FTC had nowhere to go but up,&quot; said Bruce Silverglade, legal directorof the Center for Science in the Public Interest in Washington.;    &quot;But interms of activism, it has not turned around like the Environmental ProtectionAgency or the Food and Drug Administration.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  New York Times  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Washington  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910128  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  410  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday January 28, 199100028131,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>